Question 2. Decision Trees and Random Forests

(a)

library(tree)

# Room Occupancy Training Data
training_data = read.delim("/Users/Geoff/Documents/Data Science MSc/Semester 1 October 2019/Big Data Analytics Using R (BDA)/Coursework/CW2/RoomOccupancy_Training.txt", header = TRUE, sep = ",", dec = ".")
training_data = na.omit(training_data)
training_data$Occupancy = as.factor(training_data$Occupancy)
training_data = data.frame(training_data)

# Room Occupancy Testing Data
testing_data = read.delim("/Users/Geoff/Documents/Data Science MSc/Semester 1 October 2019/Big Data Analytics Using R (BDA)/Coursework/CW2/RoomOccupancy_Testing.txt", header = TRUE, sep = ",", dec = ".")
testing_data = na.omit(testing_data)
testing_data$Occupancy = as.factor(testing_data$Occupancy)

tree.training_data = tree(Occupancy ~ ., method='class', data = training_data)
tree.predicting_using_testing = predict(tree.training_data, testing_data, type="class")
table(tree.predicting_using_testing, testing_data$Occupancy)
##                              
## tree.predicting_using_testing  No Yes
##                           No  195  16
##                           Yes  45  44
(195 + 44) / 300
## [1] 0.7966667

The predictive performance is 0.7966667. Nearly 80% of the predictions are correct and so the predictive performance is strong. The test error rate is just over 20%.

(b)

plot(tree.training_data)
text(tree.training_data, pretty=0)

It is clear that if light is below 162.875 the room will never be occupied, regardless of the other variables. If light is above 162.875 the other variables require consideration. If light > 162.875 and temperature < 22.2112 then the room will be occupied. If the room is too warm (temperature > 22.2112) then CO2 is considered alongside humidity and again temperature.

(e)

# ROC plot function
rocplot = function (pred , truth, ...){
 prediction.1 = prediction (pred , truth )
 performance.1 = performance (prediction.1 , "tpr", "fpr")
}

# Linear kernel
fitted.linear = attributes(predict(linear.model,dat_testing, decision.values = TRUE))$decision.values
plot.roc.linear = rocplot(fitted.linear, dat_testing$y)

# RBF kernel
fitted.rbf = attributes(predict(rbf.model,dat_testing, decision.values = TRUE))$decision.values
plot.roc.rbf = rocplot(fitted.rbf, dat_testing$y)

# Plotting
plot(plot.roc.linear, main="Comparing ROC Curves", col="blue")
plot(plot.roc.rbf, add=TRUE, col="red")
legend(x=.4, y=.4, col = c('blue', 'red'), lty = 20, lwd = 5,
       legend = c('Linear Kernel', 'RBF Kernel'))

AUROC values for additional comparison:

# Linear kernel workings
pred.linear = prediction(fitted.linear, dat_testing$y)
auroc.linear = performance(pred.linear, measure="auc")
auroc.value.linear = auroc.linear@y.values

# RBF kernel workings
pred.rbf = prediction(fitted.rbf, dat_testing$y)
auroc.rbf = performance(pred.rbf, measure="auc")
auroc.value.rbf = auroc.rbf@y.values

# AUROC results
auroc.value.linear
## [[1]]
## [1] 0.7833279
auroc.value.rbf
## [[1]]
## [1] 0.762556

The predictive performance of the svm classifiers trained by using the linear kernel is better when compared with those using RBF kernels. The linear kernel result (0.7833279) is closer to 1 than the RBF kernel result (0.762556) and is therefore better. Interestingly, a linear kernel is a degenerate version of RBF, hence the linear kernel should never be more accurate than a properly tuned RBF kernel. This suggests that our RBF kernel has not been properly tuned (i.e. that there is a more suitable gamma that we could use in our model).

We can see from the table above (unscaled vs scaled) and from printing each hierarchical clustering that, when comparing the two clusterings (scaled and unscaled), scaling impacts which states go into which cluster and therefore the clusters differ.

var(USArrests)
##              Murder   Assault   UrbanPop      Rape
## Murder    18.970465  291.0624   4.386204  22.99141
## Assault  291.062367 6945.1657 312.275102 519.26906
## UrbanPop   4.386204  312.2751 209.518776  55.76808
## Rape      22.991412  519.2691  55.768082  87.72916

In this situation it is advisable to scale the data as we are unsure about the relationship between each attribute (Murder, Assault, UrbanPop, Rape) - the attributes have different units of measurement. Murder, Rape, and Assault are reported as the number of occurrences per 100,000 people whereas UrbanPop is the percentage of the state’s population living in an urban area. Scaling will also avoid giving attributes with larger magnitudes more importance. In this instance, if the data was unscaled, Assault would be given more importance as it has much higher variance than the other attributes.

Question 5. PCA and K-Means Clustering

(a)

set.seed(127)
labels = c(rep(1,20),rep(2,20),rep(3,20))

X = rbind(matrix(rnorm(20*50), nrow = 20, ncol=50),
           matrix(rnorm(20*50), nrow = 20, ncol=50),
           matrix(rnorm(20*50), nrow = 20, ncol=50))

X[labels==1,] = X[labels==1,] + rep(1, 50)
X[labels==2,] = X[labels==2,] + rep(-1, 50)
X[labels==3,] = X[labels==3,] + c(rep(+1, 50/2), rep(-1, 50/2))

(b)

pr.out = prcomp(X, scale=TRUE)
plot(pr.out$x[,1:2], col=labels, main="PCA 1 & 2 Plot", xlab="PCA1", ylab="PCA2", pch=15)

(c)

kmeans.k3 = kmeans(X, 3, nstart=200)
table(clustered = kmeans.k3$cluster, original = labels)
##          original
## clustered  1  2  3
##         1  0 20  0
##         2 20  0  0
##         3  0  0 20

We can see that all three original classes (all 20 samples for each of class) fell into seperate clusters. The clusters obtained from K-means clustering are therefore identical to the true class labels.

(d)

kmeans.k2 = kmeans(X, 2, nstart=200)
table(clustered = kmeans.k2$cluster, original = labels)
##          original
## clustered  1  2  3
##         1 20  0 12
##         2  0 20  8

We can see that there is now 1 less cluster as two classes have joined to form a new cluster.

(e)

kmeans.k4 = kmeans(X, 4, nstart=200)
table(clustered = kmeans.k4$cluster, original = labels)
##          original
## clustered  1  2  3
##         1  0  0 10
##         2 20  0  0
##         3  0 20  0
##         4  0  0 10

We can now see that class 1 has been split in two, into two new clusters with each new cluster holding 10 samples.

(f)

kmeans.principal.component.k3 = kmeans(pr.out$x[,1:2], 3, nstart=200)
table(clustered = kmeans.principal.component.k3$cluster, original = labels)
##          original
## clustered  1  2  3
##         1 20  0  0
##         2  0  0 20
##         3  0 20  0

We can see that all three original classes (all 20 samples for each of class) fell into seperate clusters. The clusters obtained are therefore identical to the true class labels.

(g)

kmeans.scaled.k3 = kmeans(scale(X), 3, nstart = 200)
table(clustered = kmeans.scaled.k3$cluster, original = labels)
##          original
## clustered  1  2  3
##         1  0  0 20
##         2  0 20  0
##         3 20  0  0

The results are the same and therefore scaling doesn’t effect the clustering at all.
